column3:
# Why Learn Greek?
- the language of scripture
-- we want to hear God's voice as clearly as we can
- translations are not inspired
-- every English translation is an interpretation
-- good enough for many purposes
-- but God's voice is "muffled"

# Can I Really Learn Greek?
- yes you can!
-- you're not too old
-- you're not too bad at languages
-- you don't need a great memory
-- anyone can learn it
- what does it take?  
-- be consistent   
-- be patient  
-- be realistic

# A Familiar Cousin
- Most of us find the Greek alphabet intimidating at first
- But there are a lot of familiar letters
-- The Greek alphabet was the source of our own

# Alpha
----------
| |
======
|"ball"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks just like our letter "a"
- never a short "a" like "hat"
- always a long a like "mall" or "ball"

# Beta

[[bird[bird] ../static/images/bird.png right 200px]]

----------
| |
======
|"bird"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks like our capital "B" with a short tail
- sounds just like our "b" as in "bird"
-- later Greeks came to pronounce it like "v"

# Delta

--------
| |
====
|"dipper" / "dart"|
--------:letter_table[letter_table]

- lower case looks like our "d" tilted forward
- upper case is a triangle
-- can sometimes be confused with "A"
- sounds like our "d" as in "dipper" or "dart"

# Epsilon

--------
| |
====
|"edge"|
--------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks like our "e"
- sounds like our short "e" as in "edge"
-- never long "e" like "mere"
-- never "ay" sound like "werewolf"
-- never silent, even at the end of a word

# Iota

--------
| |
======
|"ski"|
--------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks just like our "i"
-- no dot over the lower-case 
- usually sounds like "ee" as in "ski"
-- occasionally a shorter "i" as in "pin"
-- never a long "eye" as in "mile"

# Kappa

--------
| |
======
|"kite"|
--------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks just like our upper case "K"
-- lower-case looks like a shrunken "K"
- sounds like our "k" as in "kite"

# Mu

--------
| |
======
|"mole"|
--------:letter_table[letter_table]

- lower case looks like very rounded "m" with long arm
-- careful not to confuse with our "u"
- sounds like our "m" as in "mole"

# Omicron

--------
| |
======
|"ostrich"|
--------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks like our "o"
- always sounds like our short "o" as in "ostrich"
-- never a long "o" like in "hole"
-- Greek has another letter for the long-"o" sound
- "omicron" literally means "little o"

# Sigma (final)

--------
||
======
|"snake"|
--------:letter_table[letter_table]

- this is how sigma looks at the *end* of a word
-- looks different in the middle of a word
-- a hold-over from the practices of medieval scribes
- looks like our "s" except that it curves below the line
-- the upper curve is often larger than the lower curve
- always sounds like our "s" as in "snake"
-- never like "z" as in "has"

# Tau

----------
| |
======
|"table"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks like our capital "T"
-- lower case looks like a shrunken "T"
- sounds just like our "t" as in "table"

# Upsilon

----------
| |
======
|"eeeew!"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- looks like our "u"
-- upper case looks like our "Y"
-- both our "u" and "y" come from upsilon
- sound is between "oo" and "ee"
-- like German **
-- a bit like the exclamation "eeeew!" 
-- many just pronounce like "u" in "rude"

# Rough Breathing Mark

----------
||
======
|"heart"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- Greek has no letter 'h'
-- the ones that look like 'h' actually make a very different sound
- The 'h' sound is made by a mark above the letter
-- almost always at the beginning of a word
-- only over a vowel *or* the letter

column2: Alphabet II - Greek Letters in Modern Life
column3:
# Greek Letters in Modern Life

- There are quite a few other Greek letters that don't look like any English letters
- But several of these may be familiar from their use in math and science

# Pi

----------
| |
======
|"path"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- used in math for the number 3.1415 (etc.) that lets us calculate the measurements of a circle
- looks a bit like a path leading to the horizon
-- upper is just taller and more square
- sound is just like the English "p"
-- always a hard "p"
-- never a soft "ph", even beside other letters
-- letter name pronounced like "pea" not "pie"

# Gamma
----------
| |
======
|"grass"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- used for many things in the sciences
-- including "gamma" radiation
- looks a bit like two blades of grass
-- growing up from a root under the ground
- sounds like a hard "g" as in "grass"
-- never a soft "g" as in "gem"

# Double Gamma

----------
||
======
|"spring"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- when two gammas appear together their sound changes
- sounds like "ng" in "spring"
-- not like "ng" in "angel"
- looks a bit like more blades of grass growing
-- so it must be spring!

# Gamma-Kappa Combination

----------
||
======
|"ankle"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- when  appears with  its sound changes again
-- pretty hard to pronounce a hard "g" and "k" together!
- sounds like "nk" in "ankle"
-- an "ng" sound followed by "k"

# Theta

----------
| |
======
|"thumb"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- used for several things in math and science
-- "theta waves" are one frequency of brain activity
- lower case looks a bit like a thumb 
-- cross-bar marks the thumb nail
-- upper case is more round, with a "floating" crossbar
- sounds like "th" in "thumb"
-- never "th" as in "the" or "though"
-- always "voiceless," never "voiced"

# Lambda

----------
| |
======
|"lobster"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- used for several things in math and science
-- the half-life of radioactive materials (hence in the video game "Half-Life")
-- a wavelength in physics
-- an "anonymous function" in programming
- lower case looks a bit like a lobster
-- two claws reaching down, tail at the top
-- upper case a simple upside-down "V" (don't confuse it with  or !)
- sounds like english "l"

# Psi

----------
| |
======
|"upside down"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- often used as a symbol for psychology
-- because the Greek word "psyche" starts with it: .
- looks a bit like an upside-down umbrella
-- curved umbrella with handle sticking up
- sounds like "ps" in "upside" or "oops"
-- the "p" sound is not silent (*not* like English "psychology")
-- a bit tricky at first since we don't start words with that sound combination

# Omega

----------
| |
======
|"ocean"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- familiar from theology (Jesus the alpha and omega)
-- in electricity represents an "ohm" (unit of resistance)
- looks a bit like a boat hull floating on the ocean
- sounds like the long "o" in "ocean"
-- never a short "o" as in "log"

# English Words with Greek Letters

- Now we can spell even more English words
-- remember that you're making the English *sounds* with Greek letters
-- not finding Greek "equivalents" for each letter
----------
thing|
call|
leapt|
pet|
-----------:letter_table[word_list]

column2: Greek Words II - Greek Words in English
column3:
# Recognizing Greek Words in English
- We often find multiple Greek words stuck together in one English term
- theology (theo + log + y)
--  = "God" or "a god"
--  = "word" or "reasoning"
-- so "speaking or reasoning about God"
- often Greek is used for English prefixes
-- megachurch 
--  = "big, large"

# Smooth Breathing Mark

----------
||
======
|"open"|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]

- another mark signals the "absence" of the "h" sound
-- seems a bit odd to us
- just indicates an ordinary vowel-sound
-- as in "open" or "ambulance"
-- in fact, there is a slight burst of air from the throat (in English as well as Greek)
- keep the two breathing marks straight!
-- open at the front, sounds like "open"

column2: Noun Basics - What Is A Noun?
column3:
# What Is A Noun?
- Something we may have learned in elementary school
-- but are afraid to admit we've forgotten!
- "a person, place or thing"
-- but "thing" has to be taken broadly

# Examples of English Nouns

- house, keyboard, coffee
- fire, thought, rule
- woman, fire-fighter
- city, galaxy, corner

# Proper nouns vs. common nouns

- most nouns are "common" nouns        
- "proper nouns" name a specific object in the world
-- Mary (vs. woman)
-- Toronto (vs. city)
-- earth vs. planet
- proper nouns often capitalized in English
-- we do the same in Greek 
-- but this is anachronistic (no lower-case letters!)

# Using Our 's

- We can use these Greek letters to spell out familiar English words
-- pay attention to the sounds of the word, not the English letters
-- look for Greek letters that make those sounds
-------------
bed|
deck|
deal|
mute|
-------------
- To begin with the townspeople will ask you to do the same thing to help you become comfortable with the Greek letters and their sounds

column2: Greek Words I - Sounding Out Greek
column3:
# Your First Greek Words

- Now that you've learned the alphabet, you can already sound out many Greek words
-- 
--

# Greek Is Everywhere In English
- Many English words are actually Greek transliterated
- watch for common patterns
--  becomes "y" in English (not "u")
-- often the Greek word ending dropped off
---  becomes "type"
-- endings often replaced
--- - becomes "-y" in English
- Most medical terms are Greek
--  = "a cut"
--  = "cutting"
--- so lobo-tomy (cutting the lobes)
--  = "double, in two"
--- so dicho-tomy (cutting in two)

- Answering "yes" or "no"
----------

----------

 |not bad!

--------------
|and
|and

column2: Case Basics - What Is a Case?
column3:
# What Is a Noun's "Case"?

- Not a familiar idea for English speakers
- "case" in the sense of a job, an assignment
-- the word is "on the case"
- case = a job for a noun to do in a clause
-- how does it modify the other words?
-- how does it contribute the the overall idea of the clause?
- nouns take different forms in different "cases"
-- like uniforms for different jobs
--- different endings (usually)
--- different stems (sometimes)

# Noun Cases in English?

- English does have cases (nouns play different roles)
-- subject, possessive, direct object, indirect object, etc.
- English no longer uses different word-forms to indicate a noun's case
-- "The *ball* flew."
-- "She caught the *ball*."
-- "He gave credit to the *ball*."
-- case "uniforms" only survive in English personal pronouns
----------------
I|he|she|us
my|his|her|our|our
to me|to him|to her|to us
me|him|her|us
----------------
- Why don't we use word forms to indicate a noun's role?
-- replaced by word order & prepositions

column2: Case Basics - So Why Case Forms?
column3:
# Why Does Greek Use Different Case Forms?

- English can use word order to show a word's job
-- "The girl fed the dog."
-- "The dog fed the girl."
--- two very different ideas!
- In Greek, word order doesn't tell us much
-- You can rearrange the words without changing the idea
---    
---    
-- So you need different endings to know whether a noun is the subject, object, etc.

# The "Nominative" Case

- you might already recognize this case
-- it's used as the "dictionary form" of a noun
--- 
--- 
--- 
- how do we recognize a word's *nominative* form?
-- endings
--- three different patterns of noun endings
--- we call these "declensions"
-- stem change
--- only one declension (pattern) changes more than just the ending

# Nominative Case Endings

--------------
|masculine|
||
|feminine|
||
|neuter|
--------------:nominative_bg_table

--------------
2|-|||
1|- or -||-, -, etc.|3
2|- or -|||
--------------:nominative_fg_table

# Some Implications For . . .

- the way we read English translations
-- it's important to realize what we ''can't'' tell from a translation
-- the word order is often very different in Greek
--- sometimes that flexible word order used for emphasis
- John 1:1
--------
    | "The word was God."
--------
-- "God" () is the ''first'' word in the Greek clause
-- stressing that the word was ''God'' (and not anything less!)

# Gender Confusion?

- in many languages, words have "gender"
-- a chair might be "he"
-- the sun might be "she"
- unfamiliar to many English speakers
-- usually only people and animals are "he" or "she"
-- everything else is "it" (neuter)

# Gender in French

- only a few remnants in English
-- calling a ship "she"
--- though maybe more due to personification
- if you've taken some French, this will be more familiar
-- **le** chat (always **il**)
-- **la** bibliotheque (always **elle**)

# Grammatical Gender vs. Real Gender

- There is usually no connection!
-- in French **every** cat is **le** chat (masc.) 
--- even though some are male and some female
-- every flower is **la** fleur (fem.)
-- every library is **la** bibliotheque (fem.)
--- but inanimate objects aren't really thought to be male or female
- words for human beings sometimes fit real gender
-- **la** femme (fem.), **l**'homme (masc.)
- but other times the grammatical gender still doesn't fit real gender
-- l'humain (human being), masc.
-- les gens (masc. pl.)
-- in German **das Kind** (child) is neuter! 
--- but they don't think children are genderless

# Grammatical Gender in Greek
- three genders
-- masculine
-- feminine
-- neuter
--- like German and Latin
- think of it as simply a grammatical category
-- will help us later on to line words up with their adjectives, etc.

#Pronouncing Vowel Combinations

- When two vowels go a-walking . . .
-- In both English and Greek vowels can change their sound when they appear side-by-side
-- These sound changes follow patterns
--- English: "When two vowels go a-walking, the first one does the talking"
-- These patterns are pretty inconsistent in English
--- "meat" and "fear" vs. "pear" and "bear"
-- They are much more consistent in Greek
--- this ''may'' be in part because our pronunciation of ancient Greek is artificial
--- but even modern Greek is much more consistent than English
- two vowels together can
-- make two distinct sounds (''hiatus'')
--- "c**o-o**rdinate"
--- "pr**io**r"
--- "s**ie**sta"
--- usually the two vowels belong to different syllables 
-- combine to make one simple sound (a ''monophthong")
--- "fear", "pear", "poor", etc.
-- combine to make a "diphthong"
--- a Greek term meaning "two sounds"
--- a slide from one vowel sound to another
--- stay together in the same syllable
--- "s**oi**l" 
--- "l**ou**d" (vs "pour")

# Words for Family Roles

- So far we've been learning 
-- the sounds made by letters of the Greek alphabet 
-- how to say "yes" and "no"
-- how to say "well done" and "not bad"
- Now we've learned enough of the alphabet to start learning some more Greek words
-- we're going to get to know the townspeople by talking about their places in the family

# Personal Pronouns

- what is a pronoun?
-- another word that stands for a noun
-- instead of naming something, a pointing word to refer to it quickly
- compare
-- "Maria is busy today. Maria can't finish all of Maria's work.
--- All of the uses of Maria's name are unnecessary, since we know she's the topic of conversation
-- "Maria is busy today. **She** can't finish all of **her** work.
- ''personal'' pronouns
-- the basic kind of pronoun
-- a bit confusing: can point to "things" as well as "people"

# What Is A Clause?

- The clause is the basic building-block of Greek
-- rather than the sentence
-- often the only punctuation would mark clauses, not sentences
- A clause expresses one "state of affairs" or "situation"
-- an action, event, or state
- In Greek, the verb is the heart of the standard clause
-- much more than in English

- modifier
- verb
- modifier

column2: Greek Words IV - Places in the town
column3:
# Places in the Town

- Let's make sure you understand the labels for the places you can visit in the town
---------------------------------
  |Simon's house
 |the marketplace
 |the colonnade
 |the public bath
 |the synagogue
 |the gymnasium
---------------------------------:vocab_table

# Your First Real Conversations

- Saying 'hi'
------------------------
|"Hello" (to one person)
|"Hello" (to two or more people)
------------------------:vocab_table
--  is actually a verb whose root meaning is "rejoice"
--- the greeting invites the person you meet to "rejoice" and "celebrate" that you have come together
--- of course, by the first century this is a stereotyped expression and most would use it without thinking about its original sense
- So if someone in the town says "!" you should show good manners and answer with a "!" in return.

# I Want to Learn More

- You can find more encouragement and strategies for learning Greek here:
-- Mounce, ''Basics of Biblical Greek'', 1-6  
- If you really, really want to study some flash cards as well
-- I recommend the free program [[Anki http://ankisrs.net/]]
--- uses a similar "spaced repetition" approach to the one used on this site
--- free clients for any operating system (including Linux!)
--- free cloud syncing of your decks and progress
--- free web-interface for studying your decks in a web browser
--- paid apps for iPhone/iPad and Android that also sync with your desktop app and the web
-- If you use it, consider donating to the developer or buying one of the paid mobile apps
--- no, I'm not connected with him at all - I just know what goes into developing free software!

column2: Introduction - Why Do We Find Greek Hard?
column3:
# Why Do Many Find Greek So Hard?

- In North America, many of us have never learned another language
-- We have built it up in our minds into an impossible task
-- French or Spanish at school may have just convinced us it's impossible
- Standard classroom methods don't suit everyone
-- Require a high degree of discipline and motivation
-- Require that we already know how to memorize
-- Learning is separated from regular ''use'' of what we're learning

column2: Introduction - The Approach of This Site
column3:
# The Approach of This Program

- This program is designed to meet the needs of a broader range of students by
-- providing a fun, low-intensity environment
--- no tests or quizzes
--- students move at their own pace
--- a town setting makes the interactions interesting
-- simplifying the mechanics of language learning
--- a "one stop" solution
--- no need to make flash cards 
--- no need to memorize complex paradigms
--- just one place to go - the program figures out what you need to do!
-- providing a learning environment that fits the way we learn languages
--- regular, short interactions instead of occasional "cram" sessions
--- use of the language in a conversational setting
--- immediate feedback and the opportunity to correct mistakes

column2: Introduction - So How Does This Work?
column3:
# So How Does This Work?

- Each day, log on and go to the "map"
-- click on the "hot spots" on the map to visit a location 
-- talk (type) with the townspeople you meet there
-- just follow the instructions the townspeople give you
-- that's it!
- The townspeople will tell you when it's time to . . .
-- start learning some new aspects of Greek (badges)
-- come and view some more slide sets
-- call it quits for the day (though you can always keep going if you want!)
- That's it!

# Accent Marks

- Like French or Spanish, Greek is also written with four different accent marks
--------
acute | 
grave | 
circumflex* | 
umlaut/diarresis | 
--------
*Note: Depending on the Greek font being used, the circumflex accent may look like a tilde (~) or like a downward-facing curve. There is no difference in meaning between them.
- You should not try to use these accents except in a few cases that we'll discuss later
-- 99% of the time, accents have no affect on the words' meaning
-- They are generally tricky to master 
-- The present system of marks is only a medieval invention
-- If you use them in your answers the program will not recognize the letters!
- What are accents good for?
-- they show us where to put the stress when pronouncing a word
--- just treat them all as equivalent emphasis
-- historically, the accents reflect the different tones used in Homeric and classical Greek

# Keep Learning

- You can find more about the Greek alphabet, accents, and pronunciation in the following slide decks as well as in:
-- Mounce, ''Basics of Biblical Greek'', 7-21

# Keep Learning

- You can find more about nouns in general in:
-- Mounce, ''Basics of Biblical Greek'', 22-25

# Parents

---------
father | 
mother | 
---------:table_wordlist
- Sound quite similar to our English word
-- especially if we realize that certain consonant sounds are closely related
--- p/ and f/
--- t/ and th/
-- related in the Indo-European language family
- fathers were often remote figures

# Children

- two common terms for children
----------
child| 
child| 
----------:table_wordlist
-- both are neuter
--- *may* reflect the attitude that children were "genderless" until entering the adult world at puberty
-- little difference in meaning
- also two diminutive forms
----------
little boy| 
little girl| 
----------:table_wordlist
-- notice these forms are gendered
- household slaves were often called  or even /
-- reflects the fact that they did not have adult status
-- like children, they are the property of the household father
-- constantly reinforced that social inferiority

column2: Greek Words III - Sons and Daughters
column3:
# Sons and Daughters

-----------
son| 
daughter| 
-----------:table_wordlist
- here the words are gendered
-- gender mattered in one's relationship to parents
-   would inherit the household 
-- eventually gain authority themselves as 
-- groomed for future public roles
--- early on worked with his father learning his trade
--- wealthier might be trained to read, deliver political speeches
-   would always remain dependent property
-- passed from possession of her father directly to possession of her husband
- so being God's  was different than being God's 
-- ''both'' men and women are given status of God's 
-- not just servants or dependants
--- heirs who inherit God's household

column2: Greek Words III - Brothers and Sisters
column3:
# Brothers and Sisters
--------
brother| 
sister| 
--------:table_wordlist
- masculine and feminine forms of the same word
-- only the ending is different, marking gender
-- perhaps reflecting mutual relationship of siblings

# Women and Men
- universal term for human being
----------
person| 
----------:table_wordlist
-- does not really mean "man" (as in male)
-- so properly translated "person" or "human being" in English
- a different pair of gendered terms
-----------
woman| 
man| 
-----------:table_wordlist
-- also used to mean "husband" and "wife"
--- no specific words for marriage partners
--- a man has "his woman," a woman has "her man"

column2: Greek Words III - Masters and Servants
column3:
# Masters and Servants
- one primary term for a person with power and authority over someone else
----------
master, lord| 
----------
-- public power
--- "lord" over a town or region
--- "administrator" controlling some sector of city affairs
--- one's "boss" in a workplace 
-- household power: 
--- a "master" over household slaves
--- also used for "husband" since a man was understood to be the "ruler" of his wife
-- could also be a generic term of respect
--- like English "sir"
--- implies the addressee is the speaker's social superior
-- Jews applied the term to God in all of these senses
--- Israel as God's subjects, God's servants, God's wife

column2: Greek Words III - Masters and Servants B
column3:
# Masters and Servants

- terms specifically reserved for slaves
--------------
(male) slave| 
(female) slave| 
--------------:table_wordlist
-- although often translated "servant" in English versions, almost always meant "slave" in the Roman Empire
--- few servants who were not slaves (or recently freed slaves)
-- perhaps less slavery in Judea and Galilee
--- but even there 'servants' were often in a bonded arrangement
--- not free workers: under bondholder's control
- Then terms for "child" are used
--   or (much less often)  
--   /

column2: Alphabet IV - Greek Hiatus and Monophthongs
column3:
# Vowel Combinations in Hellenistic Greek

- the default is to give neighbouring vowels as two distinctly pronounced letters
-----------------
|''ee-ah'' (IPA: ???)
|, "darkness" (skah-tee-ah)
|''ah-aw'' (IPA: a-)
|as in , "people, nation" (lah-os)
|''e-ah'' (IPA: - or -)
|, "if" (e-ahn) 
-----------------
- only a few pairs combine to make one sound (''monophthongs'')
------------------
|"oo" (IPA: u)
|, "rich, wealthy" (ploo-tahs)
|never as in "pout"  or "pour" (IPA: o)
------------------

- the few diphthongs are consistent
-----------------------
|''ah-ee'' like "high"
|as in , "child" (pah-ees)
|never as in "pail" or "mail"
|''ay'' like "pay" or "weigh"
|the same sound as 
|as in , "I raise up" (e-gay-row)
|never "ceiling"
|''e-oo''
--- as in , "gospel, great announcement"
|not "ew" or ''ee-oo''
|''oh-ee'' like "boil" or "toy"
|, "boat" (ploh-ee-ahn)
------------------------

# Iota Subscript - The Stealth Vowel

----------
|, , |
======
|--|
-----------:letter_table[letter_table]
- The letter  (iota) shifted underneath a long vowel
-- ''sub-'' (under) ''script'' (written)
-- doesn't appear under short vowels (, )
-- usually under a final letter, but occasionally in the middle of a word
- Does not change the vowel under which it appears
-- In places people had already stopped pronouncing the letter  (iota)
-- instead of changing the spelling, moved it under the previous letter
- Why bother?
-- Helps distinguish (in writing) between several different words

# Personal Pronouns

- ''personal'' pronouns
-- the basic kind of pronoun
-- a bit confusing: can point to "things" as well as "people"
- English pronouns
-----------------------
|1st person|2nd person|3rd person
singular|I|you|he|she|it
plural|we|you|they
-----------------------
- three grammatical "persons"
-- first-person "I" "me" "we"
--- the speaker or a group that includes the speaker 
--- we all start off putting ourselves first!
-- second-person "you" 
--- person/group the speaker is addressing directly
--- if we mature, start by noticing person across from us
-- third-person "he" "she" "it" "they"
--- anyone aside from you and I
- he/she/it/they are "outside" of the pair formed by "you" and "me"

# Personal Pronouns in Greek
- Appear in different "cases" just like regular nouns
-- they will behave like first- and second- declension nouns
-- but the nominative forms are irregular (don't fit the pattern)
------------------------
1st person|2nd person|3rd person
all genders|all genders|masculine|feminine|neuter
||||
------------------------
- easy to remember
--  
--- comes into English as "ego"
-- 
--- rhymes with "you"
--- starts with "s" sound like "second" person
-- /-/- 
--- root is - with typical nominative noun endings
--- source of English "auto" in "automobile" (moves itself)
- for the moment we'll only learn the singular

# Finding a Bigger Category
- In many places we'll find that any noun or pronoun can play a given role in a sentence
-- "I thanked Diodorus" / "I thanked him"
- So it's helpful to have a bigger category that includes both
----------------------
nominal
noun|pronoun|(substantive adjective) 
----------------------:pronoun_table

# Subject-Predicate vs Verb Focus
- we usually talk about an English clause as a subject modified by a predicate 
---------------------------
Subject||Predicate
Alexander||runs to the gate
---------------------------:subject_predicate_table

- subject: the person/place/thing doing the action of the verb
- predicate: everything the clause tells us about the subject
-- makes a clause seem like its goal is to describe a verbal subject
- but this way of thinking about clauses is less helpful in Greek
-- as we will learn later on, the subject is often contained in a Greek verb
-- Greek doesn't give the subject such a privileged position at the front of the clause
--- if the subject is identified by its own word it can be anywhere in the clause
-- It is quite common for the subject of a Greek clause to be left indefinite
--- the subject simply isn't the dominant focus

column2: Clause basics - a verb with modifiers
column3:
# An Alternate Picture of the Clause
- It is much easier to read Greek if we think of the verb as the focus
-- a verb (all on its own) can be a complete Greek clause!
-- the verb expresses the core "situation"
-- all of the other parts of the clause fill out our picture of that core situation
--- they "modify" (add to) the idea expressed by the verb 
---------------------
modifiers||verb||modifiers
---------------------:clause_table
- the subject of the clause is one kind of modifier
-- tells us who/what is doing the action
-- but not necessarily the most important information
---------------------
modifiers||verb||subject
---------------------:clause_table

# Verbless Clauses in Greek
- There is a second kind of clause in Greek that is less focused on the verb
-- in fact, these clauses have no verb at all!
- In a verbless clause the verb "to be" is assumed
-----------------------------
subject||predicate
||{is}|
subject||copula|complement
-----------------------------
- both subject and complement are in the nominative case
-- so an easy kind of sentence for us to start with 
- the subject and complement can be in any order
-----------------------------
 .|"Simon is a father."
 .|"Simon is a father."
-----------------------------
- In talking with the townspeople, try to mix up the word order
-- this will help you read verbless clauses more easily

column2: Greetings and Learning Names - My Name Is
column3:
# My Name Is . . . 

- You can use a verbless clause to introduce yourself
--------------------------
 |||
name|my|is|Ian
My name is Ian
-------------------------- 
- As with most expressions in Greek, the order of the words is very fluid
-- These statements all mean the same thing:
--------------------------
|   .|
|   .|
|   .|
--------------------------:table_1col
-- so try to vary your word order when you introduce yourself

column2: Greetings and Learning Names - What Is Yours?
column3:
# Your First Question

- If you need to ask someone his or her name, you would say:
-------------------------
|| |?
What|is|name|your?
What is your name?
-------------------------
-- and, again, try to vary your word order in asking the question:
-------------------------
   ?
   ?
   ?
-------------------------
- Don't worry if it takes you a few tries to get this right.
-- Just repeat a conversation step until you get it right a couple of times
